Comment:
Q: Is it better that people think God is real?

Absolutely. If you feel God is unreal you run into several problems. Firstly, you put yourself in a position where you think that the majority of people on the planet are so deluded that they worship someone who doesn’t exist.

Secondly, you put yourself in a position where you have to make up your own moral and ethics, or just be a mindles follower of the masses.

You have no basis for good or evil, right or wrong. If there is no God, it means everything is relative, which means that nothing, incuding murder and rape, ultimately is neither right nor wrong. It’s simply your opinion about it, or what is legislated about it.

Of course, in any culture murder and rape is considered wrong, but there is no basis for it. All you can say is that in this particular culture we have decided that rape and murder is wrong.

In most Western countries abortion isn’t considred murder. Or the killing of animals definitely isn’t murder. Murder only refers to killing humans. But who has decided that? Who has the right to say that cows or aimals have no souls?

Ultimately you’d have to accept that the only thing you have to look forward to in life is disease, old age and death, which basically makes your existence meaningless. If you’re born only to die, what’s the meaning of it all, except what you make of it?

So to not be marred by an endless array of existential anxieties, it’s better to think God is real.

People, like many atheists are not plagued by existential anxieties, but that’s only because they are too dumb and unintelliigent to actually think about life. They’re basically dumb animals. It doesn’t matter how many PhDs you have. If you think that God doesn’t exist, you are a dumb animal.

Finally, to think that God exists can be verified, because if God exists, He can certainly veryfyl His own existence. If you think God is unreal, not only does it make you stupid, it also makes you a blind believer.

“Both animals and men share the activities of eating, sleeping, mating and defending. But the special property of the humans is that they are able to engage in spiritual life. Therefore without spiritual life, humans are on the level of animals.” —Hitopadesa
Author: Hindus Lack Unity&Shatrubodh 🙏

Q: Can we be blessed without God?

We can be blessed by material opulence by our good karma. That’s nature’s blessings on us. But even nature can’t function witout God’s directions. So we can be blessed by different demigods, but ultimately all blessings come from God.

So, no, we cannot be blessed without God. And to be blessed by God, first we need blessings or mercy from the spiritual master and other advanced Vaishnavas.

Srila Visvanatha Chakravarti Thakur states:

yasya prasadad bhagavat-prasado / yasyaprasadan na gatih kuto 'pi

dhyayan stuvams tasya yasas tri-sandhyam / vande guroh sri-caranaravindam

Q: Where is God when people are starving all over the world?

God is where He always is - in the hearts of all living entities and in the spiritual world playing with His liberated devotees in eternal knowledge and blisss.

A better question would be - why don’t countries that waste enormous resources of land and crops to raise cattle for slaughter, stop slaughtering animals and produce food for starving people, instead?

It takes 10 kgs of plant proteine to produce one kg of meat proteine. That’s an enourmous waste of resources.

In the West trillions of dollars are spent yearly in the defence and meat-industries. A couple of billion dollars could easily feed the world’s starving population several times

The reason people starve is simply mismanagement of nature’s resources.

Why does God allow ungodly, evil forces to rule the world? Wecome to Kali-yuga - the age of quarrel and hypocrisy.

The best you can do for the planet at this time is being a vegetarian.

Comment:
Q: Who was the first person to worship a nature deity?

As far as we know people have always worhiped various gods of nature. All the ancients before us worshiped gods of nature - the Vikings, the Romans, the Greek, the Egyptians etc.

Ir wasn’t until Christianity took over in Europe that such practice was stopped as ungodly. The Church even burned people on the stake for worshiping gods of nature. They were considered witches and evil wizards. I kid you not, a woman collecting healing herbs in the forest risked being deemed a witch by the Church and burned on the stake.

In the Vedic tradition nature was considered a venerable goddess to be honored and respected. Obviously humanity is dependent on the kind cooperation of nature.

Krishna says:

In the beginning of creation, the Lord of all creatures sent forth generations of men and demigods, along with sacrifices for Vishnu, and blessed them by saying, “Be thou happy by this yajna [sacrifice] because its performance will bestow upon you everything desirable for living happily and achieving liberation. —Bg 3.10

The demigods, being pleased by sacrifices, will also please you, and thus, by cooperation between men and demigods, prosperity will reign for all. —Bg 3.11

In charge of the various necessities of life, the demigods, being satisfied by the performance of yajna [sacrifice], will supply all necessities to you. But he who enjoys such gifts without offering them to the demigods in return is certainly a thief. —Bg 3.12

The devotees of the Lord are released from all kinds of sins because they eat food which is offered first for sacrifice. Others, who prepare food for personal sense enjoyment, verily eat only sin. — Bg 3.13

All living bodies subsist on food grains, which are produced from rains. Rains are produced by performance of yajna [sacrifice], and yajna is born of prescribed duties. — Bg 3.14

Regulated activities are prescribed in the Vedas, and the Vedas are directly manifested from the Supreme Personality of Godhead. Consequently the all-pervading Transcendence is eternally situated in acts of sacrifice. —Bg 3.15

My dear Arjuna, one who does not follow in human life the cycle of sacrifice thus established by the Vedas certainly leads a life full of sin. Living only for the satisfaction of the senses, such a person lives in vain. —Bg 3.16

In former ages, the kings would perform elborate sacrifices to nature on behalf of the population. In this day and age such sacrifices are not possible due to lack of qualified priests or brahmins, so God in His infinite kindness towards the fallen souls has given a sacrifice that everyone can perform very easily and at no cost - the chanting of the holy names of God.

Hare Krishna, Hare Krishna, Krishna Krishna, Hare Hare

Hare Rama, Hare Rama, Rama Rama, Hare Hare

"This mantra, consisting of 16 words and 32 syllables, is the only means against evil in the age of Kali. After searching through all the Vedic literature, one cannot find a method of religion more sublime for this age than the chanting of Hare Krishna."

--- Kali-santarana Upanishad

The Hare Krishna mantra has replaced all sacrifies, and will secure nature’s cooperation. The reason that nature is uncooperative at this point in time, is that the vast majority of the world's population do not chant Hare Krishna. If more and more people chant Hare Krishna, nature will treat humanity more kindly. Right now nature is severe towards humans, because they have neglected to perform sacrifice to her.

It doesn't matter what you believe in - Jesus, Allah or whatever - you will be punished by nature if you don't perform sacrfice to her. And the supreme sacrifice for this age is the Hare Krishna maha-mantra
Author: Hindus Lack Unity&Shatrubodh 🙏

Comment:
Q: In ten million years, will humans still exist?

Humans will always exist, even ten millon years from now

Krishna says:

Never was there a time when I did not exist, nor you, nor all these kings; nor in the future shall any of us cease to be. --Bg 2.12

Time on earth passes through a progression of four ages, lasting together 4,32 million years. During this time, human society will gradually degenerate until now, in Kali-yuga, everything is degraded to the extent that knowledge of God is completely lost.

Fortunately, Due to Srila Prabhupada and his ISKCON - direct descendents of the bhakti-revival movement begun by God Himself - Chaitanya Mahaprabhu, 500 years ago, sanatana-dharma is now spreading like wild-fire on the planet.

This only happens once in a day of Brahma. One day of Brahma consists of 1000 yuga cycles of 4,32 million years, so one of Brahma’s days lasts 4,32 billion years.

In other words, God descends personally to planet Earth only once in 4 billion years. Because we have been fortunate enough to take birth as humans 5000 years after Krishna’s descent, we tend to forget what an extremely rare occurrence it is for the soul to be born as human.

The present Kali-age is one out of 1000 Kali-yugas, where God personally descends to planet Earth in order to display His pastimes and deliver Bhagavad Gita. And whenever Krishna descends, He comes again 4500 years later as Chaitanya Mahaprabhu, to deliver people by the Hare Krishna mantra.

So in the present Kali-yuga there will be a golden age of 10.000 years of Krishna consciousness. That period began 500 years ago with the descent of Chaitanaya Mahaprabhu in West Bengal.

It’s a work in progress, though, and it’s going to get worse before it gets better. Nature, obviously, has to rid herself of the present ungodly consumer culture, before the Golden age can really set in.

None the less, it is safe to say that being born at this time, in this particular Kali-yuga, only 500 years after God was here, is most rare and fortunate.

Shukadev Goswami says:

My dear King, although Kali-yuga is an ocean of faults, there is still one good quality about this age: Simply by chanting the Hare Krishna maha-mantra, one can become free from material bondage and be promoted to the transcendental kingdom.

Whatever result was obtained in Satya-yuga by meditating on Vishnu, in Treta-yuga by performing sacrifices, and in Dvapara-yuga by serving the Lord's lotus feet can be obtained in Kali-yuga simply by chanting the Hare Krishna maha-mantra. —Srimad Bhagavatam 12.3.51-52

Krishna says:

By human calculation, a thousand ages taken together form the duration of Brahma's one day (4.32 billion years). And such also is the duration of his night. (Bg. 8.17)

At the beginning of Brahma's day, all living entities become manifest from the unmanifest state, and thereafter, when the night falls, they are merged into the unmanifest again. (Bg. 8.18)

Again and again, when Brahma's day arrives, all living entities come into being, and with the arrival of Brahma's night they are helplessly annihilated. (Bg. 8.19)

Yet there is another unmanifest nature, which is eternal and is transcendental to this manifested and unmanifested matter. It is supreme and is never annihilated. When all in this world is annihilated, that part remains as it is. (Bg. 8.20)

That which the Vedantists describe as unmanifest and infallible, that which is known as the supreme destination, that place from which, having attained it, one never returns—that is My supreme abode. (Bg. 8.21)
Author: Hindus Lack Unity&Shatrubodh 🙏

Comment:
Q: What makes us forget that we are going to be dead someday like all those before us did?

Our attachment to the body and its gratification makes us forget about death.

People regard death as unavoidable, so they feel no need to worry about it. Forget about death, and just get on with your life. Enjoy life while you can, before you die, they say.

People, of course, know they are going to die, but they are in denial about it. They have chosen to forget about it.

Death is the last thing people want to think or talk about. Nobody talks about death, unless, of course, it’s the death of some celebrity reported on the news.

Even if a person is on his last breath, dying from an accident or some disease, what do people tell him? - easy now, everything is going to be ok.

In reality the human life-form is meant to prepare for death. Death is the final exam in the school of life. That’s what most people forget or deny - how we conduct ourselves in this life is a preparation for the next life.

People of an atheistic mentality deny this fact. Even though such a mentality is the very cause of our bondage to the material world, and its inherent miseries, they have chosen to forget about it.

The human life-form is an extremely rare opportunity, however, for the soul to solve the problem of death, once and for all. Again, most people will deny that death is a problem.

But when properly analyzed it’s our biggest problem. We may have so many problems in life - our wife leaves us, our kids are drug-addicts, we don’t have enough money, we can’t pay the rent, we can’t find work, the list goes on and on, but if I’m diagnosed with an incurable, fatal disease, all other problems immediately take a back-seat. So the biggest problem in life is actually death.

For the soul to not take advantage of the rare chance the human life-form offers the soul to become deathless, is a signal to nature that this soul doesn’t need to be a human.

Eating, sleeping, mating and defending the soul can do in any life-form, only as a human can the soul can get out of samsara, and regain it’s immortality.

“Both animals and men share the activities of eating, sleeping, mating and defending. But the special property of the humans is that they are able to engage in spiritual life. Therefore without spiritual life, humans are on the level of animals.” —Hitopadesa

Note : Don't forget Shri Hari Hara when death comes
Author: Hindus Lack Unity&Shatrubodh 🙏

Q: Why do bad and evil people never suffer in life?

You must live on another planet. Everybody suffers in life. Suffering is the inevitable result of living in a material body. Three sources of suffering are mentioned in the vedic scriptures - sufferring from our own body and mind, sufferings inflicted upon us by other living entities, and sufferings from nature (suffering inlicted by demigods).

These are general sufferings that nobody can avoid.

Apart from that, bad and evil people suffer more miseries than good and decent people.

In the material world there are no innocent people. We have all come to the material world because we have turned our backs on God. Especially in the present age of Kali, evil people thrive.

Many people come across as good people - generous and kind etc. - but one look at their dinner-tables decked with pieces of the roasted cadavers of murdered animals, shows they are not good people. In fact, anyone who thinks that humans have the right to slaughter animals on a mega-scale, simply in order to eat, is not a good person, no matter how much he gives in charity, or how well he treats his wife and kids, or his dog.

Of course, in todays world meat-eaters are not considered evil. They are simply a product of their upbringing, so they are more or less innocent. But since they support the most evil and destructive industry on the planet - the meat industry, they will partake in the bad karma involved.

In the material world the law of karma rules.

The law of karma is a natural law, and just like the law of gravity it works whether you believe in it or not.

The law of karma dictates that people create their own destinies according to their activities. Or, like it says in the Bible - as you sow you shall reap.

Note, how this statement from the Bible does not make sense without reincarnation. We reap right from our very birth. We reap a certain family, destiny, gender, nationality, abilities etc. When would we have sown that if not in earlier lives?

So the law of karma can be understood properly only in connection with reincarnation. When seen in terms of several lives, the question - how do bad things happen to good people? - poses no problem.

If bad things happen to good people in this life, it’s a reaction to bad things they did in a previous life. Similarly, if bad people are seen to enjoy a happy life, they are enjoying the karmic reactions of pious activities performed in a previous life.

For instance, take Bill Gates, he is a full fledged demoniac person. So the wealth and position he enjoys in this life must be the result of pious activities performed in his last life. Anyway, the bad karma that awaits him is staggering. He has nothing but extreme misery to look forward to. However, it may not manifest until his next life. Only time will tell.

In conclusion, here is God’s definition of a good person. How many people now a days fit that description?

Krishna says:

One who is not envious but is a kind friend to all living entities, who does not think himself a proprietor and is free from false ego, who is equal in both happiness and distress, who is tolerant, always satisfied, self-controlled, and engaged in devotional service with determination, his mind and intelligence fixed on Me – such a devotee of Mine is very dear to Me. —Bg 12.13-14
Author: Hindus Lack Unity&Shatrubodh 🙏

Q: Who are polytheists in the world other than Hindus?

The Greek were polytheists, the Romans were polytheists, the Vikings were polytheists. In fact all the ancient cultures in history were polytheists.

Now, to call somebody a Hindu i akin to calling a Christian, a Muslim and a Jewish person, say, a Jordanist. Hinduism consists of several religions and they are all monotheistic. Vaishnavas regard Vishnu or Krishna as the one Supreme God. Shaivites regard Shiva as the Supreme God. Shaktas regard mother nature personified in goddess Durga as the Supreme Goddess.

Hinduism is as varigated as all the Abrahamic religions put together.

In Hinduism different gods, called demigods are described - Ganesh, Brahma, Indra, Vayu, Varuna, Agni and others. Ganesh is the son of Shiva and is famous for removing inauspicious obstacles. Vaya is the god of wind, Varuana is the god of the seas. Agni is the god of fire. Indra is the king of the demigods, king of Heaven. Surya is god of the sun.

So in Hinduism there is the one Supreme God Vishnu or Krishna, and then there are many demigods who are like departmen heads of the different departments in the universe. They administrate the universe on behalf of God.

What unite all Hindus, however, is that they all adhere to the Vedas. There are also Hindus, called Brahmavadis or Mayavadis. They regard the impersonal Brahman as the Supreme reality, even beyond Krishna or Shiva. Actually, that is a form of atheism, as they reject that the Supreme God is personal.

Anyhow, to call Hinduism polytheistic is false in the sense that, yes, there are many gods but only one Supreme God. And the majority of Hindus know that.

Most Hindus accept Krishna’s words in Bhagavad Gita, that He is the Supreme Personality of Godhead.

Krishna says:

I am the source of all spiritual and material worlds. Everything emanates from Me. The wise who perfectly know this engage in My devotional service and worship Me with all their hearts. (Bg 10.8)

The thoughts of My pure devotees dwell in Me, their lives are fully devoted to My service, and they derive great satisfaction and bliss from always enlightening one another and conversing about Me. (Bg 10.9)

To those who are constantly devoted to serving Me with love, I give the understanding by which they can come to Me. (Bg 10.10)

To show them special mercy, I, dwelling in their hearts, destroy with the shining lamp of knowledge the darkness born of ignorance. (Bhagavad Gita 10.11)
Author: Hindus Lack Unity&Shatrubodh 🙏

Q: Why was Lord Sri Krisha not considered a god by his own relatives when he was alive?

God has two illusory potencies - maha-maya, and yoga-maya.

Maha-maya is the illusion of the material world that covers all living entities, making them forget Krishna.

Yoga-maya is the illusion of the spiritual world, making Krishna and His devotees forget who He is, so they can relate to Him in different ways.

For instance, Krishna’s parents in Vrindavan, Nanda Maharaja and mother Yashoda, relate to Krishna as their child. To enhance their parental love for Krishna, yoga-maya covers them so they don’t know Krishna is God. It’s hard to relate to your little kid in a proper way, if you know that this kid is actually God, so they are covered by yoga-maya to enhance Krishna’s pastimes with His parents.

Yoga-maya also covers Krishna making Him forget that He is God. When mother Yashoda chases little Krishna with a stick because He has been naughty, it’s not that Krishna thinks - I’m actually God, I’m just pretending to be this little kid. When Krishna is running away from mother Yashoda chasing Him, He is actually afraid of His mother. He thinks He like any other toddler.

This is the work of yoga-maya to help Krishna have more fun, acting like a human being. Of course, as Vishnu or Narayana, God never forgets He is God. But as Krishna, God forgets Himself. Krishna allows Himself to come under the direction of yoga-maya, to enhance His pastimes as a human.

Krishna can have more close and intimate relationship with His friends and girl-friends, when they don’t know He is God. Krishna has more fun with His friends and relatives wen they don’t know He is God. So Krishna covers both Himself and His close friends over with yoga-maya - the spiritual illusion, to enhance His enjoyment.
Author: Hindus Lack Unity&Shatrubodh 🙏
